Exactly, the benefit of Github is exactly what it says on the tin:<p><pre><code>    &quot;Build software better, together.&quot;
</code></pre>
Or, like it says on my Github mug:<p><pre><code>    &quot;Github: social coding.&quot;
</code></pre>
Seriously, if it&#x27;s just you the self hosting your git repos is much easier, cheaper, and you&#x27;ll have a better handle on how git actually works. However, if you&#x27;re on a team or dealing with other people, the collaborative features of Github are awesome.<p>Once again, the correct answer is &quot;use the right tool for the job.&quot;
